### CHORES

_The domestic labor that keeps a household running — shopping, cooking, cleaning, maintaining, scheduling — is invisible until it stops happening. It is also where most consumer decisions are made: which products to buy, which contractors to hire, which repairs to attempt, which to outsource. The billionaire class delegates this to staff who comparison-shop, vet vendors, and manage maintenance schedules. Everyone else does it in the margins of a full workday, making decisions under time pressure with whatever information is on the label or the first page of search results. The entries that follow turn your Agent into the household staff you don't have._

---

#### Ch-1: Shopping Your Values
*Strategy:* Research + Decide
*See also:* Ch-5: Cooking and Culinary Skills (for what to do with what you bought), Ho-3: Right-to-Repair (for durable goods), H-8: Wellness and Nutrition Coach (for dietary needs)
*My Man Jeeves:* _One might observe that every purchase constitutes a small policy decision, conducted under time pressure with information that is, at best, inadequate. The distinction between "free range" and "cage-free" eggs, for instance, is a regulatory matter that costs the consumer $2 per dozen and approximately an hour of research to verify --- a ratio that would give any reasonable person pause. The difference between a $40 toaster that expires in two years and a $90 toaster that endures for fifteen is, regrettably, invisible at point of sale and conspicuous only in retrospect. In well-staffed households, procurement is handled by persons who source by quality, ethics, durability, and price in whatever combination the household prefers. The remainder of the population is furnished with a label, a search engine optimized for advertising revenue, and eleven minutes before the shop closes. It may be worth noting that one's Agent is capable of evaluating all four dimensions simultaneously, unencumbered by sponsored results._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I need to buy [product or grocery item].
My priorities, in order: [rank these or remove ones you
don't care about]
— Price: [budget or range]
— Ethics: [labor practices, environmental impact,
  animal welfare, local sourcing]
— Durability: [how long should it last, repairability]
— Certifications that matter to me: [organic, Fair Trade,
  B Corp, union-made, specific labels]
My constraints: [where I can shop, delivery needs, timeline]
Please:
1. Recommend specific products or brands that match my priorities
2. Explain what the relevant certifications actually mean ---
   not the marketing, the standard
3. Flag any greenwashing or misleading labels I should watch for
4. If my priorities conflict (e.g., ethical + cheapest),
   show me the tradeoff honestly
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Start with one category you buy regularly --- eggs, coffee, cleaning supplies, whatever you spend the most on without thinking. Run it through your Agent once. The research compounds: once you know which brands align with your values, the weekly shop gets faster, not slower.

::: tip
Take a photo of the grocery aisle shelf or the product label and send it to your Agent. Ask: _"Which of these options best fits [your priorities]? What do these certifications actually guarantee?"_ This works in the store, in real time, on your phone.
:::


::: fairness
"Vote with your dollar" is real, but it is also a framework that works better the more dollars you have. Ethical consumption is easier at $120,000 a year than at $35,000. Your Agent will not judge your budget. If you tell it your priority is price, it will optimize for price. If you tell it your priority is ethics within a budget, it will find the best available option --- not lecture you about what you should be spending. The tool works for your values at your price point.
:::


