#### Ch-6: Optimizing Manual Chores
*Strategy:* Diagnose + Navigate (Expert Role)
*See also:* Ho-1: Maintaining Your Home (for home systems maintenance), H-8: Wellness and Nutrition Coach (when physical limitations affect chore capacity)
*My Man Jeeves:* _Domestic labor presents itself as perhaps the only category of work that is simultaneously essential, unpaid, invisible, and expected to organize itself. A factory managing the same number of recurring tasks --- laundry, dishes, floors, surfaces, bathrooms, refuse, meals, groceries --- would employ a process engineer, maintain a schedule, and follow a workflow. A household, by contrast, has one person who noticed the bathroom required attention and two who did not, together with a vague mutual understanding that "we should be better about this" --- an understanding that has not, in recorded history, produced a system. In a properly staffed household, one finds task lists, schedules, and supply inventories. One's Agent is capable of constructing the same infrastructure for the staff one actually has, which is to say, oneself._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
Act as a household operations consultant.
My household: [how many people, ages, any mobility or
health limitations, pets]
My living situation: [apartment/house, approximate size]
The chores I'm trying to manage: [list them — laundry,
dishes, floors, bathrooms, kitchen deep clean, trash/recycling,
grocery shopping, meal prep, yard work, etc.]
My biggest pain points: [what falls through the cracks,
what causes friction, what takes the most time]
My schedule constraints: [work hours, when I have time
for chores, how much time per day/week I can realistically
spend]
Please:
1. Build a weekly chore schedule that distributes tasks
   across available time --- don't front-load everything
   into Saturday
2. For each task, give me the minimum effective version
   (how to do it well in the least time) and how often
   it actually needs to happen
3. Identify which tasks can be batched, which benefit from
   a fixed day, and which are better done in small daily
   increments
4. Flag where the household friction is likely coming from
   and suggest a system, not a conversation
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Print the schedule or put it on a shared digital calendar. The system only works if everyone in the household can see it. Run it for two weeks before adjusting --- most chore systems fail because they get revised after three days, before anyone has had a chance to build the habit.

::: science
Occupational therapists have studied household task optimization for decades, primarily for clients with physical or cognitive limitations. Their findings apply to everyone: batching similar tasks reduces transition time, fixed schedules reduce decision fatigue, and "clean as you go" systems outperform "cleaning day" systems for maintaining baseline tidiness. The research consistently shows that the obstacle to a clean house is not motivation --- it is the absence of a system that works with your actual energy and schedule.[^ch6-1]
:::


::: tip
Ask your Agent for the _minimum effective frequency_ for each chore. Toilets need cleaning weekly. Baseboards do not. Sheets should be washed every one to two weeks. The inside of your oven can go months. Most people either clean everything too often (burnout) or nothing often enough (chaos). Your Agent can build a tiered schedule: daily tasks (5 minutes), weekly tasks (30 minutes each), and monthly tasks (one per weekend).
:::


::: fairness
The unequal distribution of domestic labor is one of the most documented findings in sociology. In heterosexual households, women perform roughly 60% of housework even when both partners work full-time --- and the gap is larger for households with children. This entry builds systems, not guilt. But a system that makes the labor visible --- on a calendar, with names attached --- does more to equalize the distribution than any conversation about "helping out more" ever has.[^ch6-2]
:::


